3. Create a data frame containing the most dangerous vehicle make in each state. The number of persons fatally hit in the vehicle make is used to assess the (non-)safety of a make. Make sure to handle the missing values appropriately. (look up variable MAKE)

    dangerous_vehicle <- fatally_hurt %>%
        filter(!is.na(MAKE)) %>%
        group_by(STATE) %>%
        count(MAKE) %>%
        top_n(1) %>%
        select(STATE, MAKE)
## Selecting by n
    dim(dangerous_vehicle)
## [1] 54  2
    head(dangerous_vehicle)

## 2     2    12

According to the FARS manual, 99 is unknown make. We replace NA with 99 to get rid of NA for the MAKE

The number of accidents during the week is lowest near the being of the week starting on monday. It seems that people get in more accidents on the weekend and when it is approaching.

The most accidents seem to occur around 6-8pm. This may be due to people coming home from work and not having the same attention that they did in the morning.

Looking at the chart, we can see the males (left) are in almost double the number that females are. This may be due to men being more aggressive and having more driving jobs (like trucking for example)

7. Now plot a choropleth map of the number of deaths on a county level. Also explain what you find.

    counties <- map_data("county")
    deaths <- fatally_hurt %>%
        group_by(COUNTY) %>%
        summarise(dead = n())
    #str(deaths)

    counties1 <- glcs_us %>%
        mutate("County Code" = as.numeric(`County Code`)) %>%
        select("County Name", "County Code") %>%
        left_join(deaths, by = c("County Code" = "COUNTY"))
    #str(counties1)

    counties <- counties %>%
        mutate(subregion = toupper(subregion)) %>%
        left_join(counties1, by = c("subregion" = "County Name"))
    #str(counties)

    counties %>% ggplot(aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, fill = dead)) +
        geom_polygon(color = "white", size = 0.1)

There seems to be less deaths in west side of the us. Maybe this is due to the geography not being as flat as the rest of the us, making the roads more dangerous
